<br>
But I digress.  While reading, what do I hear but the most annoying ruckus.  Upon recognition, I knew it was none other than Zippus Maximor, disturber of libraries and gnome of mental stature in direct proportion to the physical.  Needless to say, I did not appreciate the disturbance.  However, and I am sure you understand, knowing the nature of this cretin, asking the fool to desist would only provoke him further.  And so, I consciously and intentionally violated the Posture sub-statute VII.c of the rules set forth by the Council on Proper Courtly Conduct and Gentlemanly Manner, specifically the stature regarding comport while engaged in Proper Study in a Library.  In short, I slumped in my seat and hid behind the Volume in front of me so as not to be noticed.  Childish and peurile, perhaps, but effective, as I was unnoticed.<br>
<br>
Prhaps this was my undoing, or perhaps it was to my utmost benefit.  It seems this Maximor was in company of several of the Zuns, the irregular gnomish clan recently inducted into the League of Honour.  I paid very little heed to their conversation, except upon hearing my very name mentioned.  My attention and curiosity were subsequently piqued...as was my outrage!<br>
<br>
As it turns out, this most banal of gnomes, Zippus Maximor, has been passing rumor that Tanare, that most childishly unkempt and ceaselessly chattering Elf, and I, Sergian Singian-Smythe, a proper Erudite gentleman, are somehow romantically linked!  Can you imagine such scandalous insult to my character?!<br>
<br>
Confrontation was inevitable and, indeed, warranted.  Carefully marking my page, and properly closing and aligning the tome on the table in front of me, I approached this gaggle of gnomes.  At first, Maximor seemed surprised to see me, but then, of all things, the insufferable fool grinned!  I, of course, pressed him for immediate recant of such affront, as well as for written denunciation of this notorious fabrication, to be distributed through proper channel and posted publicly, as well as to have himself subjected for censure by the afformentioned Council on Proper Courtly Conduct and Gentlemanly Manner.  Spreading scandalous falsehoods is a severe violation of subsection XIII.d, as you well know!  Punishments, and I quote, &quot;can include, but are not limited to, fine and revokation of Library privileges for a period not to exceed two (2) months.&quot;<br>
<br>
